This requires grounding the agent in a physics-aware world model with object properties and action preconditions/effects. Define objects with mass and mobility attributes: `table.movable = false` (anchored/heavy), `cup.movable = true`. Model the `place(cup, table)` action using STRIPS-style operators: preconditions are `on(cup, table) = false`, effects are `on(cup, table) = true` — no effect on `position(table)`. The frame assumption (closed-world with explicit effect lists) ensures unlisted properties remain unchanged; since `position(table)` is not in `place`'s effect list, it stays constant. Reinforcement this with a constraint: actions only change `position(x)` when `x.movable = true` and an explicit `push/pull` force exceeds a threshold. For a learning agent, train on physical simulation data (e.g., PyBullet) where placing a 0.3 kg cup on a 20 kg table produces zero table displacement, letting the agent generalize that `Δposition(table) ≈ 0`. At inference, the agent queries its causal model: `cause(move(table)) → force > threshold`, observes `place(cup)` produces negligible force, and concludes `¬move(table)`.
